            <div id="dsq-comment-message-43231" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Jay, I&#8217;d bet you are right on your first guess, but the second point is a bit harsh. Pruning parts of the business that are not working doesn&#8217;t necessarily reflect on the people involved. Sure, sometimes it does, but often, the business idea just didn&#8217;t work, just as a lot of startups fail, and that isn&#8217;t seen as a negative reflection on those who were part of them. Many of them go on to great success.  So it&#8217;s important to separate the business/financial side from the personal performance side.</p>
