    <li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-43202">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-43202" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-43202">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-43202">JoeBuck</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-43202" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-43202" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Well, I don&#8217;t know. Yes, you&#8217;ve learned valuable lessons, but perhaps you were a company that people loved precisely because you didn&#8217;t know all those things up front. There were things that were more important to you than just the bottom line. Perhaps if you had a really serious, efficient CFO at the beginning your financials would have been better and the world would have been worse off.  You might not have put out a book on every obscure Unix tool; perhaps Maker Faire would have been seen as too much of a gamble. Perhaps fewer people would be employed and there would be more dollars for you and fewer dollars for some of the less competent people who used to work for you. How much efficiency do we really need?  Enough to sustain a business, yes. But I see too many companies with good products, a good culture and happy customers ruin themselves because of the imperative from investors to grow, grow, grow.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment even depth-2" id="dsq-comment-43210">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-43210" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-43210">
http://radar.oreilly.com                <span id="dsq-author-user-43210">timoreilly</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-43210" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-43210" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>I hear you, Joe. But we&#8217;ve continued to do those things even as we have become more disciplined.  There is no question, though, that a lot of our success did indeed come from our ignorance of &#8220;how things are done.&#8221; But I believe it&#8217;s possible to have a deep connection to your values and mission while still running a tight ship.  The pathology you describe is common &#8211; putting growth or profit before all else &#8211; but I can assure you that O&#8217;Reilly is a long way off from that being a problem. We are still dreamers who want to make a better world.  We just know that we can do that more effectively if we do our dreaming in a disciplined way.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment odd alt depth-3" id="dsq-comment-43225">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-43225" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-43225">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-43225">Robin de Jongh</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-43225" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-43225" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>A lot of interesting points. On this one you made about structured dreaming though &#8211; I suspect habitual dreamers will tell you it is impossible to dream in a structured way. How do you catch a cloud and pin it down? From a business perspective, growing into a large company is impossible to do while keeping the dreaming alive, and there is overwhelming evidence that this is the case for all companies that grow beyond a certain size. I also suspect that this is true of O&#8217;reilly (the company). However, if this creative culture is what you really still want to have; if these dreams are whom you really wish to cultivate; splitting the monolith into smaller startup-like units is perhaps the best and only option you have.  I suspect this is what you did with Make. Allow each unit to be able to innovate, and the way to do that is to allow each to have the potential to fail or succeed big. Management of all forms inhibits the right to fail. In my experience the right to fail is the key to innovation. Dreams are the private property of individual employees, and the only way to have them give over those dreams to the collective is to provide a seed bed&#8230; to cultivate and not to manage.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
