    <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-43209">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-43209" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-43209">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-43209">Derek Douville</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-43209" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-43209" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Some of the best management career advice I ever received was to focus on emulating success, but move on quickly from failures. In essence, there are finite ways to succeed and unlimited ways to fail. As long as your failures can lead to a successful outcome, you are then able to focus only on using the successful experiences as a template for more predictable outcomes. One example would be during a hiring phase, to find candidates that are a good talent fit, understand why your top performers are great talent fits and then look for those elements in the interview.</p>
</div>
        </div>

