    <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-43233">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-43233" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-43233">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-43233">Bruce E</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-43233" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-43233" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Hi Tim &#8211; I enjoyed the article and am glad to hear O&#8217;Reilly is thriving. I think often and fondly of my time at O&#8217;Reilly, even if in the end it was not the right fit. I&#8217;ll never forget how nice and welcoming you were to my kids when we visited during Foo Camp, which I truly appreciated. </p>
<p>To those who don&#8217;t know Tim personally, he is one of the most genuinely nice people you will ever meet. Which is not to say I think he did everything right&#8230;frankly, I disagreed with quite a few things. </p>
<p>I won&#8217;t go into them here, but I remember one interaction because it seemed so out of character for Tim. He said to me, &#8220;Bruce&#8230;at some point, you&#8217;re just going to have to accept that this is an employer-employee relationship&#8221; (in the sense that the issue we were discussing was no longer up for debate).</p>
<p>I think one thing that fails to come through in the article is how much Tim hates to play the heavy (although I&#8217;m sure he has evolved in the last 10 years, as he highlights the many ways he has become a tougher manager/businessman). </p>
<p>On paper, O&#8217;Reilly should have been the perfect home for me. I thought I was joining a tech company, when in fact I was joining a publishing company.  I was just too MIT-ish in a company that was more Harvard-ish.</p>
<p>The fact that I wasn&#8217;t right for the role or the company culture was both a surprise and a real disappointment. We both would have been better off if we had come to that realization sooner, or acted on it immediately.</p>
<p>I think in the end, the best we could hope for was to part ways amicably, and I&#8217;m glad to this day for the time Tim spent while I worked there.</p>
<p>Good luck to everyone.</p>
<p>Cheers<br />
Bruce E.</p>
</div>
        </div>

